Taiwan Stocks: Catcher Technology, Kinsus Interconnect, Hiwin

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-07-26T05:57:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-26/chunghwa-picture-tubes-da-cin-promos-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 1:30 p.m. close in Taipei.  The Taiex Index rose 110.73 or 1.3 percent, to 8,794.24,
the highest close since July 6.  Catcher Technology Co. (2474 TT) surged 6.9 percent to a
record NT$248.50. Second-quarter net income climbed to NT$2.4
billion ($83 million) from NT$839.6 million in the same period a
year earlier, the casing maker said yesterday. HSBC Holdings
Plc, Credit Suisse Group AG and UBS AG raised their share-price
estimates for Catcher today.  Chunghwa Picture Tubes (2475)  Ltd. (2475 TT) gained 1.5 percent to
NT$3.46, the biggest advance since June 19. The flat-panel
company signed an agreement with  Intellectual Ventures  that
gives it access to 35,000 intellectual property assets to boost
its defense against lawsuits, the Taoyuan, Taiwan-based company
said in a press release yesterday.  Hiwin Technologies Corp. (2049)  (2049 TT) jumped 7 percent to
NT$374.50 on speculation the ball-bearing maker will report
improving sales next quarter, said Titan Horng, an analyst at
IBT Securities Co. Third-quarter sales may rise about 9 percent
to 10 percent from the previous three months, Horng said in a
telephone interview from Taipei. President H.C. Tsai didn’t
answer calls to his office.  Kinsus Interconnect Technology Corp. (3189)  (3189 TT), which makes
chips for smartphones, climbed 6.9 percent to NT$123.50 after
client Broadcom Corp. forecast third-quarter sales that topped
analysts’ predictions.  ProMOS Technologies Inc. (5387)  (5387 TT) advanced 6.5 percent to
NT$0.66. The chipmaker reached agreements with creditor banks,
the Commercial Times reported, without saying where it got the
information. ProMOS will cut its capital to NT$5 billion and
repay half of its syndicated loans with new shares, the
newspaper said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
